.TH CUSTODIA-CLIENT 1 "@DATE@" "Custodia @VERSION@" "Custodia Manual"
.SH NAME
custodia-client \- encrypted Custodia client CLI
.SH SYNOPSIS
.SY custodia-client
.I command
.RI [ arguments ...]
.YS
.SY custodia-client
.B version
.YS
.SY custodia-client
.B --version
.YS
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B custodia-client
is the end-user encrypted secret CLI for Custodia. It performs application
cryptography locally and sends only ciphertext, crypto metadata, and opaque
recipient envelopes to the server.
.PP
Passing
.BI --client-id " ID"
uses the standard per-user profile directory:
.PP
.EX
$XDG_CONFIG_HOME/custodia/ID
.EE
.PP
or, when
.B XDG_CONFIG_HOME
is not set:
.PP
.EX
$HOME/.config/custodia/ID
.EE
.PP
Explicit paths and
.BI --config " FILE"
remain available for advanced automation.
.PP
The server is not a public-key directory. Recipient public keys are loaded
from local files supplied by trusted out-of-band exchange.
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.B mtls generate-csr --client-id ID [--private-key-out FILE --csr-out FILE]
Generate a client-side mTLS private key and CSR. Without explicit output paths,
write
.I ID.key
and
.I ID.csr
under the standard client profile directory. Transfer only the CSR to the
server/admin signer workflow; keep the private key on the client host.
.TP
.B mtls install-cert --client-id ID --cert-file FILE --ca-file FILE [--cert-out FILE --ca-out FILE]
Install the signed mTLS client certificate and public CA certificate into the
standard client profile directory. Without explicit output paths, write
.I ID.crt
and
.I ca.crt
under the profile directory.
.TP
.B config write --client-id ID --server-url URL [--out FILE --cert FILE --key FILE --ca FILE --crypto-key FILE]
Write a reusable local JSON profile for mTLS and local crypto paths. With only
.B --client-id
and
.BR --server-url ,
paths are derived from the standard client profile directory.
.TP
.B config check --client-id ID|--config FILE
Validate the profile, HTTPS URL, local mTLS certificate/key pair, CA bundle,
and optional crypto key without contacting the server.
.TP
.B key generate --client-id ID [--private-key-out FILE --public-key-out FILE]
Generate a local X25519 application key pair. Without explicit output paths,
write
.I ID.x25519.json
and
.I ID.x25519.pub.json
under the standard client profile directory.
.TP
.B key public --client-id ID --private-key FILE --public-key-out FILE
Derive and write a local public key file from a private key file.
.TP
.B key inspect --key FILE
Print key metadata and public-key fingerprint without exposing private material.
.TP
.B doctor --client-id ID|--config FILE [--online]
Run read-only diagnostics for a local client profile. The default mode validates
local profile, mTLS files, CA bundle and crypto key without contacting the server.
Pass
.B --online
for an mTLS current-client reachability check.
.TP
.B secret put --client-id ID|--config FILE --name NAME --value-file FILE
Encrypt a plaintext file locally and create a secret.
.TP
.B secret get --client-id ID|--config FILE --secret-id ID [--out FILE]
Read a secret, decrypt locally, and write plaintext output with mode 0600.
.TP
.B secret share --client-id ID|--config FILE --secret-id ID --target-client-id ID --recipient ID=FILE
Grant another client access by rewrapping local key material to the target
recipient public key.
.TP
.B secret version put --client-id ID|--config FILE --secret-id ID --value-file FILE [--recipient ID=FILE]
Create a new encrypted version. Include every recipient that should keep access.
.TP
.B secret versions --client-id ID|--config FILE --secret-id ID [--limit N]
List secret version metadata.
.TP
.B secret access list --client-id ID|--config FILE --secret-id ID [--limit N]
List access grant metadata.
.TP
.B secret access revoke --client-id ID|--config FILE --secret-id ID --target-client-id ID --yes
Revoke future server-side access for a target client. Already downloaded
material may remain decryptable offline.
.TP
.B secret delete --client-id ID|--config FILE --secret-id ID --yes
Delete a secret from future server-side reads.
.SH GLOBAL OPTIONS
.TP
.BI --client-id " ID"
Local client id. For most commands this selects the standard per-user profile.
Also accepted through
.BR CUSTODIA_CLIENT_ID .
.TP
.BI --config " FILE"
Reusable client profile. Also accepted through
.BR CUSTODIA_CLIENT_CONFIG .
.TP
.BI --server-url " URL"
Custodia API base URL.
.TP
.BI --cert " FILE"
Client mTLS certificate.
.TP
.BI --key " FILE"
Client mTLS private key.
.TP
.BI --ca " FILE"
Custodia CA certificate. For normal client profiles, use a readable client-local copy such as
.I ca.crt
instead of loosening /etc/custodia permissions.
.TP
.BI --crypto-key " FILE"
Local X25519 private key JSON.
.TP
.BI --recipient " ID=FILE"
Recipient public key file for share/version operations.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B XDG_CONFIG_HOME
Base directory for standard Custodia client profiles. Defaults to
.IR $HOME/.config .
.TP
.B CUSTODIA_CLIENT_ID
Default local client id.
.TP
.B CUSTODIA_CLIENT_CONFIG
Default reusable profile path.
.TP
.B CUSTODIA_BASE_URL
Default API base URL.
.TP
.B CUSTODIA_CLIENT_CERT
Default mTLS client certificate.
.TP
.B CUSTODIA_CLIENT_KEY
Default mTLS client private key.
.TP
.B CUSTODIA_CA_CERT
Default CA certificate.
.TP
.B CUSTODIA_CRYPTO_KEY
Default local X25519 private key file.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I $HOME/.config/custodia/ID/ID.config.json
Reusable local client profile written by
.BR "custodia-client config write" .
.TP
.I $HOME/.config/custodia/ID/ID.key
Client-side mTLS private key generated by
.BR "custodia-client mtls generate-csr" .
.TP
.I $HOME/.config/custodia/ID/ID.x25519.json
Local application private key. Keep mode 0600.
.TP
.I $HOME/.config/custodia/ID/ID.x25519.pub.json
Local application public key to exchange out of band.
.SH SECURITY NOTES
Plaintext, DEKs, mTLS private keys, application private keys, and recipient
public-key discovery remain outside the server. Avoid writing plaintext to stdout
on shared terminals.
.PP
Revoking access is future server-side revocation. For strong revocation, create
a new encrypted version without the removed recipient.
.SH EXAMPLES
Create and validate a local client profile:
.PP
.EX
CLIENT_ID=client_alice
custodia-client mtls generate-csr --client-id "$CLIENT_ID"
# Transfer the CSR to the server/admin host, sign it, then transfer back the signed certificate and CA.
custodia-client mtls install-cert --client-id "$CLIENT_ID" \
  --cert-file client_alice.crt --ca-file ca.crt
custodia-client key generate --client-id "$CLIENT_ID"
custodia-client config write --client-id "$CLIENT_ID" \
  --server-url https://vault.example:8443
custodia-client config check --client-id "$CLIENT_ID"
.EE
.PP
Create and read a secret:
.PP
.EX
custodia-client secret put --client-id client_alice \
  --name demo --value-file secret.txt > create.json
custodia-client secret get --client-id client_alice \
  --secret-id SECRET_ID --out secret.readback.txt
.EE
.SH VERSION
Custodia version: @VERSION@
.br
Build commit: @COMMIT@
.br
Build date: @DATE@
.PP
Runtime version is available with:
.PP
.EX
custodia-client version
.EE
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B 1
Runtime or API failure.
.TP
.B 2
Usage error.
.SH SEE ALSO
.IR docs/DOCTOR.md ,
.BR custodia-admin (1),
.BR custodia-server (1),
.BR custodia-signer (1)
